				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$e^+ + e^-\rightarrow {\bar{\nu }} \,\nu $$\end{document} process becomes very important and indeed dominates after stars begin burning carbon in the core. In all cases, a non-vanishing neutrino magnetic moment could contribute significantly to the neutrino production, since it would provide a direct coupling between neutrinos and photons.

