SuperCDMS operated Ge and Si bolometers of hundreds of grams at the Soudan Underground Laboratory in US. A 70 eV threshold was achieved exploiting the Neganov–Trofimov–Luke (NTL) effect at high bias voltage (HV) to convert charge into heat; results down to 1.5 GeV were presented from different analyses [280, 281]. Very small Si detectors (0.93 and 10.6 g) have been recently operated on surface considering nucleon and electron scattering and dark photons [282, 283]. The operation of SuperCDMS at SNOLAB in Canada with different types of Ge and Si detectors (up to ∼\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
