Dark scalars appear in models for naturalness, dark matter, axions, and electroweak baryogenesis, among others. Various anomalies can be explained by the presence of additional scalars, often through interactions with the Higgs boson, such as the gamma-ray excess at the center of the galaxy measured by the FermiLAT [705] and the antiproton excess in cosmic rays measured by the AMS-02 experiment [706] (see for example Ref. [707]). The ATLAS, CMS and LHCb experiments at the LHC are able to probe new scalars in the mass range O(100MeV-100GeV)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
